UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2637
1 A RESOLUTION declaring that the Kentucky Supreme Court's opinion and order
2 of April 6, 2026, is unconstitutional.
3 WHEREAS, since the adoption of Kentucky's first Constitution in 1792, the power
4 of impeachment has been vested solely in the House of Representatives; and
5 WHEREAS, the adoption of the Judicial Article amendments in 1975 did not limit
6 or circumscribe the authority of the House of Representatives to exercise its power of
7 impeachment; and
8 WHEREAS, the framers of the Judicial Article amendments in 1975 left no room
9 for doubt that the adoption of the amendments did not limit or circumscribe the authority
10 of the House of Representatives to exercise its power of impeachment when they
11 included a revised Section 109 of the Constitution of Kentucky to state, "The
12 impeachment powers of the General Assembly shall remain inviolate"; and
13 WHEREAS, no opinion, order, or other action of the Court of Justice can limit or
14 circumscribe the Constitution of Kentucky's vesting of the impeachment power in the
15 House of Representatives and the power to try impeachments in the Senate; and
16 WHEREAS, any opinion, order, or other action of the Court of Justice that purports
17 to limit or circumscribe the Constitution of Kentucky's vesting of the impeachment power
18 in the House of Representatives and the power to try impeachments in the Senate is void
19 and ineffective because it is unconstitutional and directly contradicted by the plain,
20 inescapable, and unambiguous language of the Constitution of Kentucky; and
21 WHEREAS, on March 20, 2026, the House or Representatives adopted House
22 Resolution 124 which approved as adopted five Articles of Impeachment against Julie
23 Muth Goodman, Circuit Judge for the 22nd Judicial Circuit consisting of Fayette County;
24 and
25 WHEREAS, the five Articles of Impeachment in House Resolution 124 explained
26 how Judge Goodman's conduct constituted "misdemeanors in office" which are
27 impeachable under Sections 66, 67, and 68 of the Constitution of Kentucky; and
