1 WHEREAS, on April 6, 2026, the Kentucky Supreme Court issued an opinion that
2 purported to exercise the Court's supervisory writ power under Section 110 of the
3 Constitution of Kentucky, which is textually limited in scope to "writs necessary in aid of
4 its appellate jurisdiction, or the complete determination of any cause, or as may be
5 required to exercise control of the Court of Justice," over the General Assembly, where
6 the Kentucky Supreme Court's supervisory writ power cannot reach; and
7 WHEREAS, the Kentucky Supreme Court purported to enjoin the General
8 Assembly from exercising powers that the Constitution of Kentucky vests solely in the
9 General Assembly, which the Kentucky Supreme Court has no power to enjoin; and
10 WHEREAS, the Kentucky Supreme Court purported to announce a newly-invented
11 principle that the scope of the impeachment power is limited to "the rarest of
12 circumstances in which a sitting judge has committed either an actual, indictable crime or
13 an offense in office constituting the most reprehensible moral turpitude," which is a
14 principle that the Kentucky Supreme Court has no authority to invent, announce, or
15 enforce; and
16 WHEREAS, the Kentucky Supreme Court's opinion of April 6, 2026, encroaches
17 on and attempts to usurp powers that the Constitution of Kentucky vests solely in the
18 General Assembly, not in the Court of Justice;
19 NOW, THEREFORE,
20 Be it resolved by the House of Representatives of the General Assembly of the
21 Commonwealth of Kentucky:
22 Section 1. This honorable body affirms that the impeachment powers of the
23 General Assembly remain inviolate and declares that those powers cannot be limited,
24 circumscribed, or otherwise violated by the Kentucky Supreme Court or anyone else.
25 Section 2. This honorable body declares that the Kentucky Supreme Court's
26 opinion of April 6, 2026, is unconstitutional, null, and void.
27 Section 3. This honorable body declares that House Resolution 124 and the
Page 2 of 4
XXXX 4/14/2026 5:46 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2637
1 Articles of Impeachment against Judge Goodman were properly adopted and remain
2 valid.
3 Section 4. This honorable body declares that when a judge abuses the powers of
4 the office she holds, she commits a misdemeanor in office for which impeachment and
5 removal from office is warranted, consistent with the first Article of Impeachment set
6 forth in House Resolution 124.
7 Section 5. This honorable body declares that when a judge defies binding
8 precedents established by the highest courts of this Commonwealth, she commits a
9 misdemeanor in office for which impeachment and removal from office is warranted,
10 consistent with the second Article of Impeachment set forth in House Resolution 124.
11 Section 6. This honorable body declares that when a judge defies statutes
12 enacted by the General Assembly and defies rules of the Kentucky Court of Justice, she
13 commits a misdemeanor in office for which impeachment and removal from office is
14 warranted, consistent with the third Article of Impeachment set forth in House Resolution
15 124.
16 Section 7. This honorable body declares that when a judge interferes with the
17 rights and powers of the grand jury, trial court jurors, attorneys, and others to perform
18 their respective roles with the Court of Justice, she commits a misdemeanor in office for
19 which impeachment and removal from office is warranted, consistent with the fourth
20 Article of Impeachment set forth in House Resolution 124.
21 Section 8. This honorable body declares that when a judge abuses the powers of
22 the office she holds; defies binding precedents from the highest courts of this
23 Commonwealth, statutes enacted by the General Assembly, and rules of the Kentucky
24 Court of Justice; and interferes with the rights and powers of the grand jury, trial court
25 jurors, attorneys, and others to perform their respective roles within the Court of Justice,
26 she commits a misdemeanor in office for which impeachment and removal from office is
27 warranted, consistent with the fifth Article of Impeachment set forth in House Resolution
Page 3 of 4
